text: The way movies/tv shows depict the relationship between these two historical figures exhausts me. Every few years it's like the public is forced sympathize with one over the other. Some years Mary is the passionate, independent spirit who became an unfortunate victim and Elizabeth is the awful schemer who mercilessly ordered Mary's head to be chopped off. Other years Mary is the naive, politically inexperienced and impulsive fool who is solely to blame for her own doom and Elizabeth as the wise, cautious and more realistic queen, has no option but to contrive a reason for Mary's execution in order to secure her own rule. I guess this new movie is going to be more sympathetic towards Mary so it's back to thinking Elizabeth was unduly harsh and ruthless. Whatever. Ultimately it's James I who benefits - even this famous rivalry between two powerful women still ends with a man controlling both countries. Go figure.

text: As one of the greatest romantic and tragic figures in European history, I have always been fond of Mary (though for the times she lacked the utter ruthlessness needed to survive in a male dominated world of twisted political machinations, say, nothing has changed much has it?!). Her grandson Charles I was another tragic romantic figure, as well as her great grandson, and great-great grandson. Something about the Stuart bloodline...they were romanticists, not really reality based. I look forward to this film, and I wonder if it can be able to truly capture historical truth. A previous movie of Mary, which starred Vanessa Redgrave was good, but not factual entirely. History gets twisted over time, and film makers embroider to make things more palatable for modern audiences. I wish they could just tell it truthfully.

text: I absolutely love historical fiction and I expect there to be inaccuracies in these types of films for entertainment and story purposes.  However, as a historian I don't think I'll be able to enjoy this due to the extreme level of inaccuracies portrayed just in this short trailer.  It's basically not historical fiction at all, it's just fiction using some historical names for its characters, no different than Abraham Lincoln vampire slayer.  Mary probably didn't have a Scottish accent.  She moved to France when she was 5 years old, and lived there until she was almost 18.  She's known for her French ways and manners, due to spending so much time in the French court.  Even if she had stayed in Scotland her whole life, like most 16th century Scottish nobles she wouldn't have such a strong accent.  Mary and Elizabeth were never friends, and they never met each other in real life.  And why is the film trying to argue that it was men that poisoned this friendly relationship between the two?  There were many factors that caused strife between the two, including Mary's claiming of the English throne and the threat she posed to Elizabeth, the religious conflict going on in Britain between Catholics and Protestants (Mary was Catholic and Elizabeth was Protestant), and the alliance between Scotland and France (England's enemy).  Overall it feels like the movie is saturated with leftist propaganda with its inaccurate multiculturalism and the vilification of all the male characters.  So while I'd love to watch a historical fiction film about Mary, I think I'll have to skip this one...

text: Ooook. Where to start? Mary would've had a French accent since she was raised in the French court as the betrothed of the Dauphin. The Scottish accent is ridiculous. Elizabeth and Mary NEVER met in person, and Elizabeth agonized and agonized about signing Mary's death warrant until she had no choice. Mary had been colluding against her with Catholic zealots, and Francis Walsingham had irrefutable proof. Had Elizabeth not signed the death warrant, her power and influence would've been considerably diminished, leaving her open to other rebellion. The meeting scene is ridiculous. Saoirse would've been better cast as Elizabeth. I wanted to like this, but the historical inaccuracies are glaring and insulting. Thumbs down, way down.

text: As someone that's possibly read too much about the Tudors, this trailer is full of inaccuracies and fiction. Perhaps they enjoy the idea of two thick people arguing in a cafe over 'facts' as per a movie they saw once. (Cousin) Mary and Elizabeth never met in person. It was all via correspondence and ambassadors. Mary was from all accounts i've read nothing like this outspoken character Saiorse portrays. She was far more meek and indecisive. I was excited to see this film when i heard about it, but now i'll watch it in a year or two after its release, if i need a laugh during a night of insomnia.

text: So... Safe to assume this will be about as historically accurate as Abraham Lincoln: Vampire Hunter and not nearly as fun. Seriously, I love studying this period in history, especially the story of these two women, and this trailer made me CRINGE so much. (Mary, sweetie, why are you wearing armor?)  I'm mostly just tired of the takes on these two women. In the end, the movie will inevitably force the viewer to side with one over the other. Mary will be portrayed as a naive innocent or a scheming, prettier rival, and Elizabeth will be cast as the jealous, cruel monarch or the level-headed but reluctant executioner (spoilers!). Seems like they're going with Mary as the one you should side with in this one. I just want one movie that has them face off and not vilify one over the other. Have the audience struggle with questions over who they should sympathize with. That would actually show them as human and would provide real substance.  Also, why are they seemingly pushing the narrative that jealous mens drove them apart? Wouldn't it be more interesting if these two had actual ambitions of their own? Maybe start eyeballing each others thrones while struggling with other tense political situations and the fact that they are technically family (although from a messed up family)? Not to say men weren't involved, they were, but if you're going to tell the story of Mary and Elizabeth have it actually be about Mary and Elizabeth! Doing this just makes them look like pawns in someone else's game!  In the end, this just looks like a ton of Oscar Bait, and not even good Oscar Bait. Shame too. This could have made for an interesting story... Maybe someday Hollywood will do it right, but I'm not holding my breath.
author: Dinadan - History and Myth nerd

text: Despite the star power, this has the makings of an absolute disaster. Apart from the obvious historical inaccuracies, framing Elizabeth and Mary as women shattering the glass ceiling of kingship is silly - powerful women like Queen Isabella and Mary's own mother (Mary of Guise) and mother-in-law (Catherine de Medici) had commanded men and nations before them. Furthermore, Mary's authority never as consolidated as Elizabeth's, due in part to her own incompetence and lack of judgment. Mary is a great tragic figure in history, and the film would have been much more interesting without involving Elizabeth.

text: I was super excited about this movie until I saw the HUGE historical inaccuracy in the trailer: Mary and Elizabeth speaking to one another face to face‚Äî something they never did in real life. They only ever corresponded through letters, despite how much they told each other they wished to meet in person. It was known to be true for Mary, who genuinely viewed Elizabeth as her sister, but for Elizabeth the thought of Mary stepping foot on English soil terrified her, as she thought that Mary would cause an uproar in her supporters who believed that she should be on the English throne‚Äî not Elizabeth. On the flip side, Elizabeth avoided journeying to Scotland out of the fear of assassination or imprisonment.   I just want ONE historical movie that actually follows the history it‚Äôs reenacting, not create fake scenes for dramatic effect.

text: I keep reading people in the comments creating about ‚Äúhistorical accuracy‚Äù, which I feel really limits you to the huge possibilities of enjoying a potentially powerful film. Firstly, I doubt that a large team of filmmakers with a vast budget of millions will have begun making this film without the simple knowledge of this subject. As is evident, almost everyone knows / thinks these two never met. This is based on a historical event, but the story makers can adapt whatever the hell they like in order to make the film they choose. It is their creation, their art. Who‚Äôs to say the director didn‚Äôt make this with the idea of what these two figures would have said to each other had they ever met?  People love to act smart and try and dissect films (before even seeing them), but you‚Äôve got to take every adaptation with a pinch of salt. If it was to be a through and through historical film, you‚Äôd be watching a documentary. Think about the volume of idiots who shunned Gladiator for its ‚Äúinaccuracies‚Äù, missing the vast deal of emotional power it held over so many audiences.   My advice is, take a breath, watch this trailer again and seek for something else other than faults. You‚Äôre missing out on the enjoyment of life by being picky.  Also, feel free to not berate me for expressing a sensitive opinion to filmmaking. I‚Äôm also a human and don‚Äôt deserve any ignorant hate speech. Cheers.

text: EXPLANATION FOR THOSE WHO ARE WHINING ABOUT HOW INACCURATE THEIR MEETING IN THIS MOVIE IS:  From indiewire.  Ronan and Robbie were kept apart throughout production and rehearsals aside from the one scene they share together. The ‚ÄúLady Bird‚Äù star shot her portions of the film in Scotland, while Robbie filmed in England. The two actresses made the decision to be kept apart so that their characters‚Äô one meeting would feel as powerful as possible on set and on camera.  Historians believe Elizabeth and Mary never met in real life, but Rourke told EW she was inspired by¬†the 19th-century Friedrich Schiller play ‚ÄúMary Stuart,‚Äù which includes a fictional scene of the two characters talking face-to-face on stage.  ‚ÄúThe whole conception of the film for me was around that meeting,‚Äù Rourke said. ‚ÄúWe really wanted to have¬†our¬†version of that famous scene, with these two women looking at each other and being confronted with their choices ‚Äî their personal choices, their political choices. It‚Äôs a moment that‚Äôs deeply personal.‚Äù
author: Alexandro Tirador

text: Any reference to her Guises relations who constantly introduced Mary as the Queen of England whilst in France? This attitude was the first of a series of faults which continued to widen an already existing rift between Elizabeth Tudor and Mary Stuart.  I read and re-read John Guy's book of the Queen and whenever I read it I always say wtf did she do... When marrying Darnley, when not imprisoning Bothwell for the assassination, when letting him stage the rape at the river Almond and then marrying him and finally deciding to throw her faith at her cousin's mercy.  If these main turning points are included in the film along with Rizzio's murder followed by the Queen's most formidable escape to Dunbar on horseback heavily pregnant, the explosion at Kirk O'Field and Cecil's constant haranguing of Elizabeth against Mary, then I'm in !  I don't give a heck about Mary's meeting with Elizabeth,  Saoirse's Scottish accent and deep blue eyes when we know  Mary had neither, nor the presence of the black courtiers as these are little details when compared with the actual facts.

text: For those not up to date on history, let me give you a taste of the complete nut case Mary was, copy pasted from 'ARose ForEpona's'  comment,    -    Declared herself queen of England with zero basis and purely on the basis of being Catholic.    Alienated her nobles and people.     Married a spoilt immature drunk, arranged his murder when she grew tired of him, acquitted the murderer then MARRIED him.    Was forced to abdicate by her exasperated nobles, escaped house arrest where she would have been comparatively safe, barged into England uninvited where she had little to no friends or supporters, to throw herself on Elizabeth's mercy; only to openly and in cold blood plot to assassinate her and usurp her throne with her only defence being, 'I'm a Queen, you can't touch me.'    Elizabeth had no choice but to execute her, a decision that she AGONISED over, and still brought down the wrath of Spain upon her (Liz won that one too though.) Mary had not a tenth of Elizabeth's shrewdness, statecraft, foreign policy or common sense. All she had going for her were beauty and charm, and they deserted her quickly enough. She'd grown up cosseted and pampered as well as Catholic in France, (Which means she should have a French accent as well) how could she hope to rule Protestant Scotland or her subjects?     -    So rather than see that, we're going to see a glorified SNP propaganda piece with the beautiful innocent and fierce Mary be martyred by the murderous evil English led by Queen Elizabeth, who rather than shown as the interesting and indpendent woman she was, is made to look like a clown and behave irrationally. It's an nothing more than a steaming pile of crap.    And It doesn't matter if it's not meant to be historically accurate, nowhere does it say that it's 'inspired by real events', it's going to be taken seriously just like Braveheart was when people were literally burning English flags in the street.

text: Jesus people  Do your research if you're going to bring up "facts" 1. Mary Stuart was a red head. 2. Her accent was a mix of Scottish and French  3. Technically Mary and Elizabeth did meet, when Mary fled to England for protection.  4. Elizabeth didn't want to kill Mary. She signed the death certificate but kept it secret. Parliament went through with the execution without her knowledge and the one who gave the order was later imprisoned.  5. Elizabeth agreed to name James VI of Scotland as her successor after his birth. Mary agreed to give up her claim to the English throne as long as her son was recognized as the rightful heir. This agreement is one reason why Elizabeth I never married. With a male heir, she no longer required a husband and no one questioned her rule except for the die hard Catholics that wanted Mary on the throne. This is my family history. I've been researching these two for God only knows how long. Being a descendant of the Stuart's (which are related to the Tudors) knowing the actual history of them is my obsession. I swear I should've become a historian.

text: This film is a load of rubbish. The English Court shown as a stately place with well dressed courtiers but the Scots Court portrayed as primitive, barbaric place with courtiers dressed like scruffs.  Illustrations exist of how Holyrood Palace looked in Mary's time and it was absolutely nothing like how it appeared in the film. Mary's rooms are still in existence and have panelled walls and yet the film showed them as being stone walls, even cave like in parts. There wasn't even a stair up to the door, just rocks that people had to climb. The Scots Court was never an opulent affair but it was regarded as one of the most sophisticated in Europe, mainly thanks to the Renaissance King, James IV and Scotland's close ties to Europe.

text: DO NOT WATCH THIS FILM - UNLESS YOU ENJOY FICTION / FANTASY.  I expected some dramatisation - much like the Tudors.  Unlike the Tudors which was broadly based on historical fact, this movie has virtually NO historical fact AT ALL.  In fact, this film should be entitled 'a work of fiction'.  Amongst other things - here is the HUGE list of historic 'errors' this film has:-  1) Elizabeth never named an 'heir' to the throne.  Oddly the film says that she did - she named James, the son of Mary.  Then the film comes up with factual text at the end saying she didn't do that after all.  Confused?  So was I.  Utter nonsense.  2) Elizabeth never met Mary EVER.  Period.  Yet according to this film she did.  er.....  no.  3) At the end of the film (Marys execution) Elizabeth says she'll remember meeting Mary fondly 5 & 20 years ago as a young vibrant queen - not the aged women she had become.   This would make the meeting in 1562 - when Mary actually Mary ran from Scotland in 1567.  3) In the so say 'meeting' (that remember never happens in reality), Elizabeth was portrayed as a rather age worn 40 something, and Mary as a very young 20 something.  This is incorrect, there was only a 9 year age gap between them.    4) James Stewart Earl Of Moray was subservient to Mary not an equal, and they were brought up in different households - the film portrays them as equals.  5) For some obscure reason the filmakers had to insert a gay scene into the film.  Yet they didn't even make it HALF believeable - with the impossibly unlikely pairing of Lord Darnley and David Rizzo!  Then to compound the ludicriousness they have Mary (after finding out Rizzo had slept with her husband) saying basically "Hey thats ok".  In reality in the 1500s, any gay relationship would have been against the bible, and he would have been put to death.  And any 'gay relationship' would not have been in a place where people could just 'walk in' - it would be under the viel of secrecy.  6)  Laughably the film shows 'Queen Elizabeth's house' as Hardwick Hall.  Unfortunately there are 2 problems with this.  Though invited on many occasions  Hardwick Hall was the one place Queen Elizabeth NEVER visited!  Oh yes and theres the other 'minor detail' of Hardwick Hall being built between 1590 and 1597, so it was begun 3 years after Mary Queen Of Scots was executed.  Yet Queen Elizabeth was shown there in the '1560s'.    7) There is no evidence Lord Darnley was gay.  He had a male valet - just like every single other nobleman in the country at the time.  But there was zero evidence of him being gay.  In the film he was.  8) Putting black people/other races in the film is a joke.  It is a bit like doing a film about african slavery, or the Zulu wars and sticking the odd white person in there for effect.  If you did that QUITE RIGHTLY black people would be OUTRAGED.  So historians are JUSTIFIABLY outraged at chucking in the odd black person for effect in what was plainly a white court.  There are also MULTIPLE pictures of David Rizzo - even though he was from Italy - he was white!

text: Mary, Queen of Scots was Queen of Scotland from 1542 to 1567. She was the daughter of King James V of Scotland and his second wife, Mary of Guise, and was the only surviving legitimate child of the king. The untimely death of her father when she was just six days old made her the Queen of Scots as a tiny infant. In the chaos following her father‚Äôs death, Mary‚Äôs great-uncle King Henry VIII of England made an effort to secure control of the throne of Scotland but his attempt was thwarted in a timely manner by Mary‚Äôs mother who acted as a regent on behalf of her daughter. Her mother, who was of French origin, fixed Mary‚Äôs marriage with Francis, the four-year-old heir to the French crown, and sent her to live in France where she was raised in the court of Francis‚Äô father, French King Henry II. She soon married Francis and when her young husband ascended to the throne upon his father‚Äôs death, Mary became the queen consort of France. However, the untimely death of her husband left Mary a widow at the age of 18 and she returned to Scotland. Mary‚Äôs reign as the Queen of Scots was fraught with political difficulties and her unwise personal choices only complicated the issues. Mary was born on 8 December 1542 to the King of Scots, James V, and his French second wife, Mary of Guise. She was the only legitimate surviving child of the king who was on his deathbed at the time of her birth. Mary was baptized at the nearby Church of St Michael shortly after she was born. James V died on 14 December 1542 when Mary was just a few days old. Thus she became the Queen of Scots as an infant. It was decided that Scotland would be ruled by regents until Mary became an adult. When Mary was six months old, she was betrothed to Prince Edward, the son of King Henry VIII of England. However, the engagement was eventually called off due to certain religious and political issues. Since Mary‚Äôs mother was French, she readily agreed when the French king, Henry II proposed that Mary be married to his son, the Dauphin Francis. Following the betrothal, Mary was sent to live in the French court under the care of her father-in-law. Mary and Francis reportedly developed a close bond from the day they met. Mary received a good upbringing in France and was trained in horsemanship, falconry and needlework. She also learned French, Italian, Latin, Spanish, and Greek, and was competent in prose and poetry. She married Francis in 1558. Her father-in-law, Henry II, died in 1559 and her 15 year old husband Francis ascended to the throne as the King Francis II and Mary, at 16, became his queen consort. Francis II died of an ear infection on 5 December 1560 leaving Mary a widow at 18. Francis‚Äô younger brother Charles inherited the throne and Mary returned to Scotland nine months after her husband‚Äôs death. She faced numerous challenges upon her return to Scotland in 1561. Having spent the major part of her early life in France, Mary was unaccustomed to life in Scotland. At that time, Scotland was torn between Catholic and Protestant factions, and Mary‚Äôs illegitimate half-brother, the Earl of Moray, was a leader of the Protestants. Mary, as a devout Catholic, was regarded with suspicion by many of her Protestant subjects, and her tolerance towards Protestants disappointed the Catholics. She fell in love with her English-born first cousin Henry Stuart, Lord Darnley and married him in 1565. This match was considered scandalous by both the Catholic and Protestant factions as Mary and Lord Darnley were first cousins. This marriage also turned her Protestant half-brother against her as Lord Darnley was also a Catholic. The marriage ran into problems from the very beginning as Lord Darnley proved to be a mean and vicious man. In March 1566, Darnley, along with a group of Protestant nobles brutally murdered Mary's Italian secretary, David Rizzio, in front of Mary who was heavily pregnant at that time. Darnley suspected that his wife was having an affair with Rizzio. Following this incidence, Mary‚Äôs marriage with Darnley broke down. When Darnley was found dead under mysterious circumstances in February 1567, murder was suspected, and Mary, along with James Hepburn, the Earl of Bothwell, Moray, Secretary Maitland, and the Earl of Morton came under suspicion. Within three months of Darnley‚Äôs death, Mary married the main suspect in her husband's murder‚ÄîJames Hepburn, Earl of Bothwell. This marriage was considered outrageous and the public turned against her. In July 1567, Mary was compelled to abdicate the throne in favor of her infant son. Mary was imprisoned in Lochleven Castle but managed to escape in 1568. She fled to England, seeking protection from her cousin, Elizabeth I. However, Elizabeth was suspicious of Mary‚Äôs intentions and had her imprisoned. Mary‚Äôs first marriage was to Francis II of France which took place in 1558. It is not known whether the marriage was consummated or not as Francis II died very young, at the age of 16. A few years after the death of Francis II, Mary married her first cousin Lord Darnley in 1565. This marriage was problematic from the very beginning though it produced one son, James VI and I. Darnley died under mysterious circumstances in 1567. A few months after the death of Darnley, she married the prime suspect in his alleged murder, James Hepburn, Earl of Bothwell. After being imprisoned by Elizabeth I, Mary was kept under strict surveillance. Her imprisonment would last for 19 long years. In 1586, Mary corresponded with Anthony Babington who was plotting to depose Elizabeth. The letters fell into the hands of Elizabeth‚Äôs spymaster Francis Walsingham, and Elizabeth began to see Mary as a threat. Thus Mary was brought to trial, found guilty of treason, and sentenced to death. Mary was executed by beheading in Fotheringhay Castle, Northamptonshire, on 8 February, 1587. She was 44 years old.üè¥Û†ÅßÛ†Å¢Û†Å≥Û†Å£Û†Å¥Û†Åø

text: I was really looking forward to this film.  Unfortunately it was very disappointing.  I know it‚Äôs a film, to be taken with a pinch of salt, but why make a film about an historical figure and get the historical facts wrong?  Mary was at the French court from an early age until aged 18, yet comes to Scotland with a Scottish accent (then again I know people from Scotland who can turn the accent on and off at will).  The film looked beautiful - the music (Handel?) was great but then Elizabeth started speaking with an Australian accent and that sort of killed if for me.  She later turned into the love child of Ronald McDonald and The Queen of Hearts from Alice and this strong, powerful character burst into tears on meeting Mary (something which historians say did not happen) and says ‚Äòooh I was jealous of your beauty‚Äô.  The performance of the ‚Äòactress‚Äô playing LIz was weak, poor, unconvincing.  David Tennant lets loose as John Knox - it‚Äôs Tennant playing Tennant in a mad wig and beard.  The little bloke playing Bothwell is weak, gives a poor performance and was not convincing as powerful man. The actor playing Rizzio as a South American effeminate, lute playing, awful singer was comical and again, unconvincing - actually Rizzio was Italian, but you wouldn‚Äôt have guessed it here.    The story was poor and flittted from scene to scene, year to year with not much going on - I sat thinking come on; she has to marry Darnley yet, and then Bothwell, how long IS this film?  The sex scenes were unnecessary - we‚Äôre all aware that that did actually have it in ye olde days. Homosexual relationship? I‚Äôm sure they happened, but no historic evidence of Darnley and Rizzio - although Edward II James I were thought to ‚Äòfavour men‚Äô.  This is a great period in British history, with two powerful women discussing/arguing about the heir to the English throne - this story isn‚Äôt portrayed  in this second rate film. It could have, and should have been told properly.
